      <ul>
        <li>Deprem tahminleri iddiası içeren paylaşımlara inanmak</li>
        <li>Sarsıntı sırasında selfie çekmek veya video kaydetmek</li>
        <li>Sosyal medyada doğrulanmamış kayıp/kayıp ilanı paylaşmak</li>
        <li>Enkaz altındaki birine müdahalesiz ağır kaldırım yapmak</li>
        <li>Depremden sonra merak amaçlı hasar bölgesine gitmek</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Ebeveynlerin Sık Yaptığı Hatalar</h2>
  <p>Deprem eğitiminde niyetin iyi olması her zaman yeterli değildir. Bazı yaygın hatalar çocuğun öğrenmesini engeller veya gereksiz korku yaratır:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Bir kez anlatıp bırakmak:</strong> Deprem davranışları tekrar edilmeden refleks haline gelmez. Yılda en az iki kez hem bilginin hem davranışın tazelenmesi gerekir.</li>
    <li><strong>Korkuyu araç olarak kullanmak:</strong> "Deprem gelirse ölürsün" gibi ifadeler öğretmez; travma yaratır. Bilgi güç verir, korku felç eder.</li>
    <li><strong>Yalnızca okulun yeterli olduğunu düşünmek:</strong> Okul tatbikatları önemlidir ancak yeterli değildir. Evde farklı senaryolar için (gece, banyo, mutfak, araç) ayrı prova gerekmektedir.</li>
    <li><strong>Tatbikatı ciddiye almamak:</strong> "Zaten biliyor" deyip geçmek yerine gerçekten zamanlayın, gözlemleyin ve geri bildirim verin.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Okul ile İş Birliği</h2>
  <p>Türkiye'de okullar yılda en az iki kez deprem tatbikatı yapmakla yükümlüdür. Çocuğunuzla tatbikat sonrası sohbet etmek — "bugün tatbikat nasıldı, ne yaptılar?" — hem deneyimi pekiştirir hem de evdeki prova ile bağlantı kurmanızı sağlar. Öğretmenlerle iletişime geçerek okul tatbikat takvimini öğrenebilir ve evdeki uygulamayı buna göre planlayabilirsiniz.</p>

  <h2>Sonuç</h2>
  <p>Çocuklara deprem eğitimi vermek tek seferlik bir ders değil, yaşa uygun olarak geliştirilen ve düzenli tekrarlanan bir süreçtir. Küçük çocuklar için oyun, okul çağındakiler için sorumluluk, ergenler için eleştirel düşünce ön plana çıkar. Her yaşta ortak olan tek şey şudur: <strong>bilgi kaygıyı azaltır, pratik ise özgüven yaratır</strong>. Bir sonraki tatbikatı bu hafta yapın — yarına bırakmayın.</p>

  <Fragment slot="en">
  <p>Responding correctly during an earthquake is not a split-second decision — it is a pre-learned reflex. This is true for adults, but even more critical for children: if a child can respond correctly the first time they experience an earthquake instead of panicking, it is only because they rehearsed it beforehand.</p>

  <p>In Turkey, schools conduct earthquake drills, but home preparedness is largely left to parents. This guide outlines the most effective ways to build earthquake awareness in children of different age groups.</p>

  <div class="callout info">
    <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/><line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/></svg>
    <p>The goal of earthquake education for children is <strong>not to frighten them but to empower them</strong>. A child who knows what to do does not panic — they execute the steps they have already practised. Education should produce confidence, not anxiety.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Ages 3–6: Teaching Basic Safety Reflexes Through Play</h2>
  <p>Pre-school children cannot grasp abstract concepts. Rather than explaining "what is an earthquake?" in detail, it is far more effective to teach the answer to <strong>"what do we do if there's an earthquake?"</strong> through play. At this age, the goal is just three movements: Drop, Cover, Hold On.</p>

  <div class="vis-grid">
    <div class="vis-card">
      <div class="vis-card-icon"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><polyline points="12 6 12 12 16 14"/></svg></div>
      <h3>The "Ground's Shaking!" Game</h3>
      <p>Once or twice a day, shout "the ground's shaking!" and run together under the table, protect the head, hold on. Repeated often enough, it becomes a reflex.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="vis-card">
      <div class="vis-card-icon"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M17 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-4-4H5a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v2"/><circle cx="9" cy="7" r="4"/><path d="M23 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-3-3.87"/><path d="M16 3.13a4 4 0 0 1 0 7.75"/></svg></div>
      <h3>Show the Meeting Point</h3>
      <p>Ask "where will you find us after the earthquake?" and walk there together. It could be a neighbour's house, a relative, or the school yard.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="vis-card">
      <div class="vis-card-icon"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M22 16.92v3a2 2 0 0 1-2.18 2 19.79 19.79 0 0 1-8.63-3.07A19.5 19.5 0 0 1 4.99 12 19.79 19.79 0 0 1 1.76 3.38 2 2 0 0 1 3.74 1h3a2 2 0 0 1 2 1.72c.127.96.361 1.903.7 2.81a2 2 0 0 1-.45 2.11L8.09 8.91A16 16 0 0 0 12 12a16 16 0 0 0 3.09 1.91l.41-1.41a2 2 0 0 1 2.11-.45c.907.339 1.85.573 2.81.7A2 2 0 0 1 22 16.92z"/></svg></div>
      <h3>Memorise a Phone Number</h3>
      <p>Getting at least one parent's phone number memorised is an achievable goal at this age. Teach it alongside "if you get lost, call this number."</p>
    </div>
    <div class="vis-card">
      <div class="vis-card-icon"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M4 19.5A2.5 2.5 0 0 1 6.5 17H20"/><path d="M6.5 2H20v20H6.5A2.5 2.5 0 0 1 4 19.5v-15A2.5 2.5 0 0 1 6.5 2z"/></svg></div>
      <h3>Picture Books and Animations</h3>
      <p>Picture books or child-friendly animations on earthquake safety (including official AFAD materials) help reinforce concepts in a playful, non-threatening way.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Ages 7–12: Learning Through Understanding and Taking Responsibility</h2>
  <p>Primary-school children can now grasp cause-and-effect relationships. Answering "why do earthquakes happen?" helps them understand the logic behind the rules, making learning stick. At this age the goal is knowledge plus practical drill.</p>

  <h3>A Simple Scientific Explanation</h3>
  <p>The Earth's surface is made up of large rock pieces called tectonic plates. These plates move very slowly and build up energy as they press and grind against each other. When enough energy has built up, a sudden slip occurs — we call this an earthquake. Turkey sits at the edge of two major plates, which is why it experiences earthquakes so frequently.</p>

  <h3>Practical Tasks for This Age Group</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Identify safe spots together:</strong> Go through every room and answer "where would I go if an earthquake hit right now?" Mark the safe spots together.</li>
    <li><strong>Build a family communication plan:</strong> "If there's an earthquake and you're at school while we're at home — how do we find each other?" Define the meeting point, a backup contact, and a Plan B together.</li>
    <li><strong>Prepare the earthquake kit together:</strong> Explain what each item is for; give the child responsibility for packing their own small bag.</li>
    <li><strong>Take drills seriously:</strong> Repeat school drills at home. Conduct at least two real drills per year.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Ages 13+: Realistic Preparedness and Critical Thinking</h2>
  <p>Teenagers already encounter earthquake news and misinformation on social media. For this age group, the goals are both accessing accurate information and truly knowing what to do in a disaster scenario.</p>

  <div class="dd-grid">
    <div class="dd-col do">
      <h3><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" width="16" height="16"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg> Topics to Discuss</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Which sources can be trusted? (AFAD, Kandilli, USGS)</li>
        <li>How to verify earthquake claims circulating on social media</li>
        <li>Basic first aid steps for injuries</li>
        <li>What to do if trapped under rubble</li>
        <li>How to help neighbours and elderly people</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="dd-col dont">
      <h3><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" width="16" height="16"><line x1="18" y1="6" x2="6" y2="18"/><line x1="6" y1="6" x2="18" y2="18"/></svg> What to Avoid</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Believing posts claiming to predict earthquakes</li>
        <li>Taking selfies or recording video during shaking</li>
        <li>Sharing unverified missing-person posts on social media</li>
        <li>Attempting heavy lifting on rubble without training</li>
        <li>Visiting damaged areas out of curiosity after a quake</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Common Parenting Mistakes</h2>
  <p>Good intentions are not always enough in earthquake education. Some common mistakes prevent children from learning or create unnecessary fear:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Explaining once and moving on:</strong> Earthquake behaviours don't become reflexes without repetition. Both knowledge and behaviour need refreshing at least twice a year.</li>
    <li><strong>Using fear as a tool:</strong> Phrases like "you could die in an earthquake" don't teach — they traumatise. Knowledge empowers; fear paralyses.</li>
    <li><strong>Assuming school is enough:</strong> School drills matter but are not sufficient. Home practice is needed for different scenarios — night-time, bathroom, kitchen, in the car.</li>
    <li><strong>Not taking drills seriously:</strong> Instead of saying "they already know," actually time it, watch it, and give feedback.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Conclusion</h2>
  <p>Teaching children about earthquakes is not a one-time lesson but an age-appropriate process that develops over time and is regularly reinforced. Play comes first for young children; responsibility for school-age children; critical thinking for teenagers. What all ages have in common is this: <strong>knowledge reduces anxiety, and practice builds confidence</strong>. Run your next drill this week — don't put it off until tomorrow.</p>
  </Fragment>
